Headlines.Author: Russell Gold
Headlines.Headline: Investigators Fault Blowout Preventer in Deepwater Horizon Oil Spill -- Update

PARAGRAPH.#text: Federal investigators probing the 2010 Deepwater Horizon disaster say a critical piece of safety equipment helped trigger the worst offshore oil spill in U.S. history. The report by the Chemical Safety Board, an independent investigative arm of the federal government, renews questions about the effectiveness of blowout preventers, giant sets of valves that are supposed to seal off an oil well in an emergency. The draft report concludes that the pipe running from the subsea oil well to the drilling rig through the blowout preventer, or BOP, buckled around the time a surge of natural gas from the well ignited, causing an explosion which killed 11 crew members.

Headlines.Headline: MARKET SNAPSHOT: Stocks Still Follow Crude, But For How Long?

PARAGRAPH.#text: By Kate Gibson As crude oil on Friday hit a high for the year above $74 a barrel, energy shares rallied, fueling the broader U.S. stock market toward weekly gains. But if oil continues to rise, what's been viewed as a bullish signal could turn bearish for U.S. equity investors. "If it jumps back up to $140 (a barrel,) for the U.S. economy that is broadly negative. If it drops back to $40, it's a positive in the short term, since it's a tax break for consumers and businesses. The opposite is true when prices are going up," said Ryan Brecht, senior economist North America, Action Economics.

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Blue-chip stocks slumped Friday, but gains for selected technology
shares helped the Nasdaq Stock Market end the week with a slight gain.Bonds and the dollar rallied from their early lows after U.S. Treasury
Secretary Robert Rubin indicated that he didn't expect any major currency
policy initiatives to result from meetings of senior finance officials in
Tokyo this weekend. He said that the foreign exchange language in the
post-meeting statement is likely to be "boiler plate."The remarks rekindled concerns about the instability of the Asian
financial markets and prompted investors on Wall Street to exit the market
ahead of the weekend. The Dow Jones Industrial Average fell 100.14, or
1.14%, to close at 8712.87.Losses for Walt
Disney
 led the Dow industrials' decline, after Goldman Sachs &
Co. cut its 1998 earnings estimate for the entertainment giant to $3 from
$3.10. Its shares fell 4 7/16 to 107 9/16.The Standard & Poor's 500-stock index eased 5.72 to 1100.65 and the
New York Stock Exchange Composite Index shed 3.57 to 563.92.But an increase in Goldman's earnings estimate for Microsoft
 provided the Nasdaq
composite with a boost, as it rose 8.59 to 1781.29. Microsoft shares
climbed 3 1/2 to 94 11/16 after the investment bank raised its
fourth-quarter estimate on the software company.Internet stocks also rallied, after a series of large companies,
including Disney, GTE

and AT&T
, announced they are
making plans to stake their claims on the Web. Yahoo! rose 1 1/2 to 129
1/4, while America Online
, which rebuffed a
recent takeover offer from AT&T, jumped 2 1/2 to 96 3/8.News of a $3.14 billion merger between Schlumberger
 and Camco International
 boosted
oil-services stocks amid talk of further consolidation in the sector.
Camco's shares soared 12 61/128 to 74 93/128, while Schlumberger's shares
slipped 3 11/16 to 66 1/4.Volume on the New York Stock Exchange was heavy amid active trading
associated with Friday's so-called triple-witch expiration of options and
futures contracts.Peter Cardillo, senior vice president at Westfalia Investments Inc.,
said lingering worries about Japan's troubled economy, and its impact on
other economies in the region, remain a stumbling block for Wall Street.
Fears persist that Asia's economic woes will hamper earnings growth at U.S.
multinationals, he said, adding that "until Japan offers some concrete
solutions to its problems this market is going to continue to trade
sideways."Bonds bounded higher after Treasury officials confirmed that Mr. Rubin
told the editorial board that he isn't expecting "policy actions" to come
out of Deputy Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers's visit to Tokyo this
weekend.World-wide, stocks edged lower in dollar terms. The Dow Jones World
Stock Index fell 0.65 to 188.07 as of 6:30 p.m. EDT.In major market action:Stocks
finished mixed
. Volume totaled 693.4 million shares on the Big Board, where 1,785
stocks declined and 1,179 advanced.Bonds
rebounded
. The long bond rose 1/4 point, or $2.50 per $1,000 face amount. Its
yield, which moves in the opposite direction from its price, slipped to
5.67%.The dollar
was weak
. It was at 1.7880 marks and 135.50 yen, compared with 1.7945 marks
and 137.83 yen late Thursday in New York.

Headlines.Author: Greg Ip
Headlines.Headline:
Index Gains 86.44,
While Oil Drillers
Slide on Rumors

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Stocks finished higher in a day of sharp reversals across sectors and
countries that underlined investors' skittishness. Bonds edged up and the
dollar was mixed.The Dow Jones Industrial Average climbed 86.44 points to 7487.76. But
that came after sharp moves intraday. The New York Stock Exchange's
50-point "collar" on certain computer-guided program trading was activated
three times, twice going up and once down. Volume of 642.3 million shares
retested the levels of the Bloody Monday 7.18% drop on Oct. 27.Jon Olesky, head of block trading at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, noted
that the S&P 500 fell at its lowest point to just above 900, which
stocks have resisted since slicing through it Oct. 27, then bouncing back
above it on the next day. The S&P 500 finished up 10.7, or 1.18%, to
916.66.The rest of the world zigzagged even more than the U.S. In Brazil,
stocks were up 5.3% at one point, down 3.8% later and finished 3.2% higher.
Technology stocks also gyrated.
America
Online
 plunged 6 11/16 at one point on concerns a recent
convertible bond issue could dilute earnings. It rebounded to end just 2
3/16 lower at 68 1/2.Then there were the oil-drilling stocks. The group has been a winner
this year, bouncing back from Bloody Monday to new highs. But Thursday,
rumors that Lehman Brothers oil-service analyst Paul Chambers was about to
downgrade the group triggered a stampede. The Philadelphia Stock Exchange's
oil-service index at one point was down 7%.Mr. Chambers said he only had told clients that the incremental growth
in demand for drilling services was to be found in a particular area of the
industry, which could perhaps be construed as negative for some stocks. But
he added that "every single oil-service stock was down, which tells me it
was bigger than anything I had to say. I'm basically the fall guy for
declining stock prices." Indeed, as the rumors dissipated, the group ended
down just 3.21%. Still, seven of the eight biggest dollar declines among
U.S. issues on the Big Board were drillers.
Camco
International
 fell 4 5/16 to 65 1/2;
Cooper
Cameron
 dropped 3 5/8 to 70; and
Tidewater

declined 3 3/8 to 62.Morning comments by Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan that Asia's
turmoil wouldn't have a seriously negative effect on the U.S. appeared to
have little impact on sentiment.World-wide, stocks rose in dollar terms. The Dow Jones World Stock Index
rose 0.98, or 0.62%, to 160.00.In major market action:Stocks rose
. Volume reached 642.3 million shares on the New York Stock
Exchange, where 1,510 stocks fell and 1,446 stocks rose.Bonds inched
higher
. The Treasury's benchmark long bond rose more than 5/32 point, or
$1.56 for each $1,000 face amount. Its yield, which moves in the opposite
direction of its price, stood at 6.09%.The dollar was
mixed
. It was quoted at 1.7260 marks and 125.68 yen, compared with 1.7170
marks and 126.54 yen late Wednesday in New York.

Headlines.BodyHeadline:
Index Gains 86.44,
While Oil Drillers
Slide on Rumors
